Why America's President Bush Must Not Be Re-elected
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world, and at the same time undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I have been damned by Bush's election campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a electoral program that promised a foreign policy of "humility."
If he is re-elected, this is a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the polls, America has a chance to regain respect and support from the world.
The 9/11 terrorist attacks required a strong response.
However, they also led to the process - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the issues at hand - being set aside, which is indispensable for democracy.
Bush silenced criticism by declaring it unpatriotic.
For a period of 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
As a result, he led America in the wrong direction.
Indeed, Bush essentially handed Osama bin Laden to his enemies.
The invasion of Afghanistan, where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda operated its training camps, was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy towards America were seen all over the world.
These have given way to widespread resentment.
More people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
Krieg and Occupation however bring innocent victims to the forefront.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world counts also the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Similarly, the torture of inmates in the Abu Ghraib prison was not the work of a few "rotten apples".
It was part of a system for dealing with prisoners set up by Defense Minister Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's safety is in good hands with him by addressing the fears aroused by the 9/11 attacks.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by promoting a sense of being threatened.
His election campaign assumes that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something may not be right with America if we fall for this.
For example, about 40% of Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in the 11th of September, although the 9/11 investigation commission – set up by Bush and chaired by a Republican – clearly found that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: „Wake up, America."
Don't you realize that we are being led astray?"
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from start to finish – if it ever comes to an end.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
Moreover, America was drawn into war under a pretext: no mass destruction weapons could be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America was drawn into war to liberate Iraq.
But you can't impose democracy on anyone with force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad that they are rid of him.
However, America had the duty to ensure law and order; instead, we watched idly as Baghdad and other cities were plundered.
If it were really about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the Oil Ministry, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they applied methods - such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population, causing bitterness and anger.
The Bush administration's retreats and mistakes are legion.
First the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the US tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be managed, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man who was appointed as their leader was a CIA protégé with a reputation as a "strong man" - a decision far from democratic.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to gloss over the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
Most of the western part of the country was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted incalculable damage on America, weakened its military might, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project the impression of overwhelming strength.
No longer today.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries pursue nuclear programmes with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration in many other political issues, but none of them is as important as Iraq.
The costs of the war have so far reached nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush has made a jab at John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
America is also stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats had warned Bush urgently not to march into Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that every criticism of the commander-in-chief would endanger US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: Who are we to blame for this mess?
A moment of thought would likely raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy demeanor qualify him to remain commander-in-chief of America?
